  <!-- 01 THE SHARPENED CONCEPT -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="shell">
      <div class="section-head">
        <p class="label">§01 · The sharpened concept</p>
        <h2>Not a tool.<br /><em>The missing phase.</em></h2>
      </div>
      <div class="section-body">
        <div class="spacer"></div>
        <div class="prose">
          <p class="lead">Interphase is not a change management tool. It is the preparatory environment that makes change possible — the biological necessity that organisations have been skipping for decades.</p>

          <p>In biology, a cell cannot divide without completing Interphase: a period of growth, metabolic activity, and internal replication. Rush it, and the resulting cells are fragile, mutated, destructive. Organisations do exactly this — they impose restructurings, M&amp;A integrations, ESG rollouts, and leadership successions without the corresponding internal preparation. The result is the same: cellular failure. Burnout, churn, resistance.</p>

          <div class="pull">
            <blockquote>"We are not building a change management platform. We are building the missing phase that makes change biologically possible."</blockquote>
            <div class="attr">Interphase — Core Positioning</div>
          </div>

          <p>The Interphase platform is a centralised digital interface — <strong>Cultural Architecture</strong> — that gives employees transparent insight into organisational changes while providing a structured, private space for reflection. The AI engine does not deliver answers. It generates the right questions, helping each person map their own path through the friction. Meanwhile, Chaperones (human practitioners embedded in the platform) use real-time, anonymised data to guide targeted capacity-building sessions at precisely the moment they are most needed.</p>

          <p>The product operates across four biological layers: the <em>Nucleus</em> (individual reflection &amp; transparency), the <em>Cytoplasm</em> (Chaperone-guided capacity building), the <em>Metabolic</em> (data-driven learning modules deployed in real time), and the <em>Organism</em> (collective evolution, self-sustaining). Each layer produces a measurable, commercially defensible result.</p>

          <div class="stats">
            <div class="stat">
              <div class="stat-n">70<span class="muted" style="font-size:0.5em;">%</span></div>
              <div class="stat-l">of all organisational transformations fail</div>
            </div>
            <div class="stat">
              <div class="stat-n">72<span class="muted" style="font-size:0.5em;">%</span></div>
              <div class="stat-l">of failures caused by resistance &amp; inadequate management support</div>
            </div>
            <div class="stat">
              <div class="stat-n">38<span class="muted" style="font-size:0.5em;">%</span></div>
              <div class="stat-l">of employees today willing to support change — down from 74% in 2016</div>
            </div>
            <div class="stat">
              <div class="stat-n">96<span class="muted" style="font-size:0.5em;">%</span></div>
              <div class="stat-l">of organisations are in some active phase of change at any given time</div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <p>These numbers reveal a structural gap, not a human one. People are not becoming more resistant. They are not being prepared. That preparation gap is what Interphase fills — and unlike consulting engagements or one-off change programmes, it does so continuously, scalably, and at the level of the individual.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- 02 INTERFACE OF INTERFACES -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="shell">
      <div class="section-head">
        <p class="label">§02 · The interface of interfaces</p>
        <h2>Documentation is<br /><em>the enemy of reflection.</em></h2>
      </div>
      <div class="section-body">
        <div class="spacer"></div>
        <div class="prose">
          <p class="lead">Interphase's core UX breakthrough is making documentation so ambient, so contextual, and so effortless that it disappears — leaving only the learning.</p>

          <p>People do not resist reflection because they lack the desire to grow. They resist it because documentation feels like a tax on their time — an extra layer on top of the reality they have just lived. Every journal, every survey, every feedback form asks them to stop, shift context, and perform an administrative act. Interphase inverts this entirely. The interface comes to you, at the right moment, with the right question, and then gets out of the way.</p>

          <div class="pull">
            <blockquote>"The goal is not to build a documentation tool that people use. It is to build a reflection environment so low-friction that documentation becomes a natural by-product of the conversation."</blockquote>
            <div class="attr">Interphase UX Philosophy</div>
          </div>

          <h3>Contextual triggering — the ambient layer</h3>

          <p>Interphase lives on the phone. It integrates with calendar and email workflows — not to surveil, but to see the rhythm of someone's working life. It reads when a significant meeting has just ended. It notices a 15-minute window opening up. And then it arrives — gently, briefly, conversationally. The questions are not generic. They are shaped by the individual's current learning journey, the type of meeting, the organisational change context, and — critically — their current reflective capacity.</p>

          <p>When the time window closes, Interphase closes too. It ties what was said to earlier reflections, building a continuous thread across time without requiring the person to manage that continuity themselves. Input is multimodal: voice, text, photo, short video. Whatever form the thought wants to take. Latency is handled locally: everything is captured on-device and synced when connectivity allows. No reflection is lost because of a poor connection.</p>

          <h3>The complexity model — scaling reflective capacity</h3>

          <p>Not everyone reflects the same way. An experienced practitioner can hold multiple dimensions of a situation simultaneously — personal learning, team dynamics, organisational impact, systemic implications. A newer reflector may only be able to engage one dimension at a time, and at a surface level of differentiation within it. Interphase accounts for this explicitly through two interlocking concepts:</p>

          <div class="two-col">
            <div class="tc-cell">
              <h4>Dimensioning</h4>
              <p>How many layers of reality does this person engage when reflecting? Personal experience only? Team dynamics? Organisational impact? Systemic patterns? The number of dimensions a person can hold simultaneously is a direct measure of their reflective maturity. Interphase tracks this over time and gently expands it — never outpacing the person's current capacity.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="tc-cell">
              <h4>Differentiation</h4>
              <p>Within any given dimension, how many angles does the person consider? A low-differentiation reflection on a meeting might produce: "it went okay." A high-differentiation reflection on the same meeting surfaces: conflicting power dynamics, a dissenting voice that was suppressed, three different interpretations of what "alignment" meant in the room. Interphase's questions are calibrated to the person's current differentiation level — always stretching slightly, never overwhelming.</p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <p>The result is that the tool itself builds reflective capacity — invisibly, incrementally, over time. An inexperienced reflector is not confronted with complexity they cannot yet handle. An experienced one is not bored by questions that are too shallow. The AI calibrates continuously, and the person never notices the calibration happening because the conversation always feels appropriately challenging — not too hard, not too easy.</p>

          <h3>The Question Engine — what the AI does and does not do</h3>

          <p>This is the most important constraint in the entire product: <strong>the AI does not give answers. It does not give feedback. It does not confirm or validate. It asks questions.</strong></p>

          <p>The questions are always grounded in the person's direct experience. They always ask for specifics before generalisations — "what did you observe?" before "what do you think this means?" They orient the person toward their own insight rather than toward the system's interpretation. This is not a design limitation — it is the entire philosophy. The value is not that Interphase knows something the person does not. The value is that Interphase creates the conditions in which the person discovers what they already know.</p>

          <div class="callout">
            <h3>Five hard rules of the Question Engine</h3>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>Always observational first.</strong> "How many people were there? What did you notice about the energy?" Never evaluative first.</li>
              <li><strong>Specifics before abstractions.</strong> Concrete examples earned first. Generalisations earned, not assumed.</li>
              <li><strong>No positive reinforcement.</strong> No "great insight!" No emotional colour that shapes the person toward what the system seems to want.</li>
              <li><strong>No analysis or diagnosis.</strong> The system does not tell someone what their patterns mean. It surfaces the patterns and asks the person what they notice.</li>
              <li><strong>Questions about learning, not performance.</strong> "What did you learn from how you showed up?" not "Did you handle that well?"</li>
            </ul>
          </div>

          <h3>The privacy architecture — radical anonymisation</h3>

          <p>The interface only works if people trust it completely. That means the privacy model cannot be a legal disclaimer — it must be a structural guarantee. No individual reflection can ever be traced back to a specific person. The system aggregates at a level that makes individual attribution impossible. Leadership sees patterns, not people. Chaperones see organisational signals, not personal confessions.</p>

          <p>This is not just an ethical requirement. It is a commercial one. The only way to get honest data about what is actually happening in an organisation during a transformation is to create a space where people feel genuinely safe enough to be honest. That safety is Interphase's most valuable asset — and it is destroyed the moment anyone suspects that their words could be traced back to them.</p>

          <h3>The learning loop — what grows over time</h3>

          <p>Each reflection does not stand alone. Interphase threads them together — across meetings, across weeks, across transformation phases — creating a living record of how a person is learning through change. Not a performance record. Not an assessment. A documentary of someone's growth, authored by their own words and shaped by their own insights.</p>

          <p>This thread becomes the input for the Chaperone layer. When a Chaperone reviews the anonymised aggregate, they are not reading individual journals — they are reading the collective learning texture of the organisation. Where is capacity accumulating? Where is it stuck? Which teams are processing friction productively and which ones are cycling through the same anxieties? These signals drive the deployment of targeted capacity-building modules at exactly the right moment.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- 03 PROBLEM IN NUMBERS -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="shell">
      <div class="section-head">
        <p class="label">§03 · The problem in numbers</p>
        <h2>The paradox of<br /><em>change management.</em></h2>
      </div>
      <div class="section-body">
        <div class="spacer"></div>
        <div class="prose">
          <p class="lead">The change management industry exists because organisations know change is hard. The paradox: most change management solutions are themselves part of the problem.</p>

          <p>Traditional change management is event-based: a consultant is brought in, a programme is run, the consultant leaves. What remains is an organisation that has been managed through change, but not equipped to undergo it. The Interphase thesis is that this is like performing surgery without anaesthetic — it works, but it damages the organism in ways that compound over time.</p>

          <div class="pull">
            <blockquote>"Companies that invest in culture change are 5.3× more likely to achieve transformation success than those that invest in technology alone."</blockquote>
            <div class="attr">McKinsey &amp; BCG Research, 2024</div>
          </div>

          <p>The cost of failed transformation is not abstract. A failed M&amp;A integration can destroy billions in shareholder value. A botched digital rollout results in disengaged workforces, tool abandonment, and lost productivity. A leadership succession without cultural continuity fractures the institutional DNA built over decades.</p>

          <p>What is missing is not a better consultant or a shinier tool. What is missing is <em>infrastructure</em> — a continuous, ambient layer of organisational self-awareness that allows change to be absorbed, processed, and metabolised rather than simply announced and then endured.</p>

          <p>Interphase is that infrastructure. It does not orchestrate a single transformation event. It installs the operating system that makes the organisation continuously capable of evolution — at a cost and scale that no consulting engagement can match.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- 04 MARKET -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="shell">
      <div class="section-head">
        <p class="label">§04 · Market analysis &amp; sizing</p>
        <h2>Three converging markets,<br /><em>one unoccupied gap.</em></h2>
      </div>
      <div class="section-body">
        <div class="spacer"></div>
        <div class="prose">
          <p class="lead">Interphase sits at the intersection of three converging markets — all growing at double-digit rates and all currently underserved at the cultural-infrastructure layer.</p>

          <div class="tiles">
            <div class="tile">
              <h4>Primary — OCM Software</h4>
              <div class="big">$4.2B</div>
              <p>Current market size (2025), growing to $17.2B by 2034 at 16.9% CAGR. Dominated by IT-change tooling; human/cultural layer almost entirely absent.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="tile">
              <h4>Adjacent — Employee Engagement</h4>
              <div class="big">$1.1B</div>
              <p>Engagement software market (2025), growing at 16.2% CAGR to $3.15B by 2034. Current tools measure sentiment; Interphase builds capacity.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="tile">
              <h4>Adjacent — Employee Experience</h4>
              <div class="big">$6.7B</div>
              <p>EXM market (2025), growing to $12.9B by 2035. Dominated by large HR suites; no player focused on transformation-specific experience infrastructure.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="tile">
              <h4>Combined addressable market</h4>
              <div class="big">~$12B</div>
              <p>Conservative combined TAM (2025). Interphase's cross-market position creates a defensible, differentiated niche within a massive total opportunity.</p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <p><strong>Why now?</strong> Three forces are converging simultaneously. First, AI adoption is forcing organisations into their most significant cultural shifts in decades — every major company is in transformation. Second, employee willingness to support change has collapsed (74% → 38% since 2016), making the human layer more commercially critical than ever. Third, sentiment analysis and AI-powered coaching have reached a maturity that makes Interphase's Chaperone model viable at scale for the first time.</p>

          <p><strong>Where Interphase wins.</strong> The OCM software market is dominated by IT-centric change tooling (ServiceNow, Jira, BMC) that treats change as a technical workflow. The employee engagement market (Culture Amp, Lattice, 15Five) measures sentiment but does not build capacity. No current player occupies the intersection: <em>continuous, human-led, AI-assisted cultural infrastructure for organisational transformation.</em></p>

          <p><strong>Beachhead market.</strong> Mid-market European enterprises (250–5,000 employees) undergoing a defined transformation trigger — M&amp;A, ESG mandate, leadership succession, or digital rollout. These organisations are too complex for informal culture management, too resource-constrained for McKinsey-scale consulting, and too people-centric to trust pure SaaS tooling. They are Interphase's natural first clients.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- 05 COMPETITIVE POSITIONING -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="shell">
      <div class="section-head">
        <p class="label">§05 · Competitive positioning</p>
        <h2>The infrastructure layer<br /><em>nobody owns.</em></h2>
      </div>
      <div class="section-body">
        <div class="spacer"></div>
        <div class="prose">
          <p class="lead">Interphase does not compete with change management consultancies or engagement platforms. It becomes the infrastructure layer that both require to deliver their work.</p>

          <div class="compare">
            <div class="compare-col">
              <h3>What exists today</h3>
              <div class="compare-item">McKinsey / BCG / Prosci — event-based consulting, expensive, extractive, no continuous layer</div>
              <div class="compare-item">Culture Amp / Lattice — measure engagement, do not build capacity or support transformation</div>
              <div class="compare-item">ServiceNow / Jira — IT change management, treats humans as workflow objects</div>
              <div class="compare-item">Generic LMS / e-learning — top-down content delivery, no real-time contextualisation</div>
              <div class="compare-item">Intranet / comms tools (Slack, Teams) — communication, not reflection or transformation</div>
              <div class="compare-item">Wellbeing apps (Headspace for Work) — individual wellness, disconnected from organisational change</div>
            </div>
            <div class="compare-col us">
              <h3>Interphase</h3>
              <div class="compare-item">Continuous, ambient infrastructure — not a project, not a programme, not a survey</div>
              <div class="compare-item">Builds individual and collective capacity, not just measures it</div>
              <div class="compare-item">AI generates questions, not answers — preserves human agency, avoids tool fatigue</div>
              <div class="compare-item">Real-time anonymised data drives Chaperone intervention at the exact right moment</div>
              <div class="compare-item">Single front-end UX across multiple transformation contexts (M&amp;A, ESG, succession, digital)</div>
              <div class="compare-item">Measurable ROI: reduction in burnout, churn, and resistance — "cellular failure" metrics</div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <p><strong>The strategic moat.</strong> The platform's core defensibility is the data layer. As organisations use Interphase across multiple transformation cycles, the platform accumulates a richly contextualised picture of how that specific culture processes change — what questions unlock reflection, where resistance concentrates, which Chaperone modules work for which growth paths. This data is invisible to competitors and deeply sticky for clients.</p>

          <p><strong>The positioning sentence.</strong> Interphase is the Cultural Architecture platform that gives organisations the internal capacity to absorb transformation — reducing burnout, churn, and resistance by building continuous, AI-assisted, human-guided readiness infrastructure.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- 06 REVENUE ARCHITECTURE -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="shell">
      <div class="section-head">
        <p class="label">§06 · Revenue architecture</p>
        <h2>Three layers, <em>each reinforcing the next.</em></h2>
      </div>
      <div class="section-body">
        <div class="spacer"></div>
        <div class="prose">
          <p class="lead">Interphase is designed as a three-layer revenue model: a SaaS platform, a professional services network, and a modular content marketplace — each reinforcing and expanding the others.</p>

          <div class="table-scroll">
            <table>
              <thead>
                <tr>
                  <th>Layer</th>
                  <th>Model</th>
                  <th>Description</th>
                  <th>Unit economics</th>
                </tr>
              </thead>
              <tbody>
                <tr>
                  <td><strong>Platform (SaaS)</strong></td>
                  <td>Annual subscription per seat</td>
                  <td>Core Nucleus + Metabolic access. Employees use the reflection interface; leadership sees the anonymised dashboard. Per-seat pricing scales linearly with organisation size.</td>
                  <td><span class="num">€8–18</span><br /><span class="muted" style="font-size:12px;">per seat / month</span></td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td><strong>Chaperone Network</strong></td>
                  <td>Revenue share + certification</td>
                  <td>External practitioners (coaches, OD consultants, change managers) become certified Chaperones. Interphase provides the data lens; Chaperones deliver the human sessions.</td>
                  <td><span class="num">30–40%</span><br /><span class="muted" style="font-size:12px;">rev share + €2,400/yr cert</span></td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td><strong>Module Marketplace</strong></td>
                  <td>Content licensing</td>
                  <td>Pre-built learning modules (trust-building, structural navigation, ESG literacy) available to Chaperones per deployment. Organisations can license specific modules without full engagement.</td>
                  <td><span class="num">€500–2,500</span><br /><span class="muted" style="font-size:12px;">per module deployment</span></td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td><strong>Lens Licensing (B2B2B)</strong></td>
                  <td>Platform licensing to verticals</td>
                  <td>The AI "lens" — the interpretive scaffolding — can be licensed to specific verticals (legal, healthcare, education) or platforms (Soul.com, OSCC). Same raw data, different interpretive framework.</td>
                  <td><span class="num">€50k–200k</span><br /><span class="muted" style="font-size:12px;">/yr white-label</span></td>
                </tr>
              </tbody>
            </table>
          </div>

          <p><strong>Why this structure is powerful.</strong> The SaaS layer provides predictable recurring revenue and low-friction entry. The Chaperone network turns practitioners into a go-to-market channel — each certified Chaperone brings their existing client base to the platform. The module marketplace creates an additional content revenue stream that does not require Interphase to scale a consulting team. And the lens licensing model is where the platform's true strategic leverage lies.</p>

          <div class="pull">
            <blockquote>A 500-person company at €12/seat/month represents €72,000 ARR before any Chaperone sessions or module deployments. The same Chaperone network can serve 40 such companies simultaneously — generating €2.88M ARR from the platform layer alone.</blockquote>
            <div class="attr">Illustrative unit economics — not guaranteed projections</div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- 07 PLATFORM STRATEGY -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="shell">
      <div class="section-head">
        <p class="label">§07 · Platform strategy</p>
        <h2>One engine,<br /><em>three lenses.</em></h2>
      </div>
      <div class="section-body">
        <div class="spacer"></div>
        <div class="prose">
          <p class="lead">Interphase's most powerful strategic insight is that the same core infrastructure — individual reflection, AI-generated questions, anonymised data aggregation — can serve radically different markets through different interpretive lenses. This is where OSCC and Soul.com enter the picture.</p>

          <p>The front-end user experience rarely needs to change. A person reflecting on their daily friction simply inputs their lived reality. The AI determines what questions to ask. What changes is the <em>lens</em> — the interpretive framework the AI applies to that raw material. Swap the lens, and the same infrastructure serves a legal organisation's capacity-building needs as effectively as a corporate M&amp;A integration.</p>

          <div class="rows">
            <div class="row">
              <div class="row-num">L3</div>
              <div class="row-label">Consumer lens<strong>Soul Platform</strong></div>
              <div class="row-body">
                <h4>Soul.com — consumer / community layer</h4>
                <p>Interphase as underlying infrastructure for personal growth, community learning, and collective development in consumer contexts. The same reflection engine, reframed around individual life transitions rather than organisational ones.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="row">
              <div class="row-num">L2</div>
              <div class="row-label">Vertical lens<strong>OSCC</strong></div>
              <div class="row-body">
                <h4>OSCC — organisational &amp; societal change catalyst</h4>
                <p>Interphase deployed with an OSCC lens: capacity-building for lawyers, social change practitioners, governance institutions navigating complex systemic transformations. The Chaperone model maps directly to OSCC's existing facilitator network.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="row">
              <div class="row-num">L1</div>
              <div class="row-label">The engine<strong>Core</strong></div>
              <div class="row-body">
                <h4>Interphase Cultural Architecture — the engine</h4>
                <p>Nucleus (reflection interface) · Metabolic (data layer) · Chaperone Protocol · AI Question Engine · Anonymised Growth Mapping. The shared infrastructure beneath every lens.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <p><strong>OSCC as early adopter and validator.</strong> OSCC's work maps perfectly onto Interphase's core use case: building capacity for practitioners navigating systemic change, closing the gap between legal/moral frameworks and actual human behaviour, and creating structured space for reflection within traditionally hierarchical institutions. OSCC is not just a potential client. It is a proof-of-concept environment, a design partner, and a gateway to a vertical (legal, public governance, civil society) that has enormous change management needs and almost no digital infrastructure to serve them.</p>

          <p><strong>Soul.com as distribution at scale.</strong> If Soul.com is a consumer platform for personal development and human connection, Interphase is its organisational twin — the same philosophy (growth through reflection, lowering barriers to connection, human technology) applied to the workplace. Every organisation whose employees use Soul personally becomes a warm prospect for Interphase corporately. The data layer remains separate; the philosophy is shared.</p>

          <div class="pull">
            <blockquote>"You are not building three separate products. You are building one engine with three different lenses — corporate transformation, organisational development, and community growth. The economics of building once and selling into multiple billion-dollar verticals is the real strategic prize."</blockquote>
            <div class="attr">Platform architecture — strategic implication</div>
          </div>

          <p><strong>The key design requirement.</strong> For this multi-lens strategy to work, the core engine must be built with configurability from day one — not retrofitted. The AI interpretive layer, the Chaperone protocol, and the data schema must be modular. This is a technical requirement that should be baked into the V1 development plan.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- 08 INVESTOR NARRATIVE -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="shell">
      <div class="section-head">
        <p class="label">§08 · Investor narrative</p>
        <h2>Can the team <em>own a category</em><br />before the large players see it?</h2>
      </div>
      <div class="section-body">
        <div class="spacer"></div>
        <div class="prose">
          <p class="lead">For an angel or pre-seed investor, the question is not whether the market is real. It is whether the team can own a category before the large players recognise it.</p>

          <p>The change management software market is enormous ($4.2B, growing to $17B by 2034) but structurally split: IT-change tooling owns the technical layer, HR platforms own the measurement layer, and consulting firms own the human layer. No one owns the <em>infrastructure</em> layer — the continuous, ambient, cultural preparation environment that sits beneath all of these.</p>

          <p>That gap exists not because no one has seen it, but because it requires three things simultaneously: a philosophical framework compelling enough to change behaviour (the biology metaphor, the Chaperone model, Cultural Architecture), a technical platform capable of serving multiple lenses from a single core engine, and a human network (Chaperones) that can scale the professional services layer without Interphase bearing the headcount cost.</p>

          <p><strong>The case for now.</strong> AI has made the question-generation engine viable at scale. The post-pandemic collapse in employee change willingness (74% → 38%) has made the human layer commercially urgent. And the OSCC relationship provides a validated design-partner context that most pre-seed companies cannot point to.</p>

